VET 436 — Small Mammal Medicine
Laboratory Manual
UC Davis School of Veterinary Medicine — 2025

Hugues Beaufrere, Michelle Hawkins, David Guzman, Krista Keller, Ariella Darvish, Marina Liles

This laboratory manual accompanies the VET 436 Small Mammal Medicine course at UC Davis. It contains handouts for three hands-on laboratory sessions covering the clinical anatomy, physical examination techniques, and dentistry of rabbits and rodents.
Labs Included

Topic
Focus




Lab 1
Clinical Anatomy
Prosections of ferret, guinea pig, rat, and rabbit with dissection


Lab 2
Physical Examination & Clinical Techniques
Rabbit handling, full physical exam, venipuncture, nasolacrimal flush


Lab 3
Dentistry of Rabbits & Rodents
Oral anatomy, occlusal adjustments, incisor extraction




Note: These materials are designed to complement the lecture content delivered in VET 436. Students should review pre-lab videos and lecture notes prior to each session.

lab1/.title: Lab 1: Clinical Anatomy
lab1/.body:
Lab 1: Clinical Anatomy
VET-436 / 2025
Hugues Beaufrere, Michelle Hawkins, David Guzman, Krista Keller, Ariella Darvish, Marina Liles

For the first hour, you will have four 15-minute presentations on small mammal anatomy using a prosection of a rabbit, ferret, guinea pig, and rat.
The prosections depict some of the anatomy that was covered in the lectures. In this lab, you will be able to translate knowledge introduced in the lecture to the real anatomy on the cadaver.
For the second hour of the lab, you will be dissecting a rabbit and a rat.

lab1/outcomes.html.title: Learning Outcomes
lab1/outcomes.html.body:
Learning Outcomes

Perform a thorough post-mortem examination in a rabbit
Become familiar with the anatomical similarities and differences of the rabbit, guinea pig, rat, and ferret
Locate clinically relevant anatomical features of each species

lab1/ferret.html.title: Ferret Anatomy
lab1/ferret.html.body:
Ferret Anatomy

Evaluate the coat -- any thinning? Endocrine alopecia is common in ferrets and can be associated with adrenal disease.

Evaluate the location of the heart in the thoracic cavity -- the heart is located very caudally compared to other species. This is clinically relevant for radiographic interpretation and cardiac auscultation.

Evaluate the gastrointestinal tract of this carnivore. A very simple, short GI tract that is typical for a carnivore. The jejunum and ileum are indistinguishable and are coiled together as the jejunoileum. There is a lack of a cecum and appendix. The ileocolic junction is only differentiated by the region where the ileocolic and jejunal arteries join.

Evaluate the location of the adrenal glands, the blood vessels surrounding the adrenals, and their relationship with other organs -- what is the relevance to common diseases?
The right adrenal gland lies craniomedial to the right kidney and is closely associated with the caudal vena cava. The left adrenal gland lies ventromedial to the cranial pole of the left kidney. Adrenal disease (adrenocortical neoplasia or hyperplasia) is one of the most common conditions in ferrets. Surgical adrenalectomy, particularly of the right adrenal gland, is challenging due to its intimate association with the vena cava.



Ferret adrenal glands and their relationship with the kidneys and ureters.

Gently palpate the pancreas for nodules -- what is the clinical relevance?
Insulinoma (pancreatic beta-cell tumor) is one of the most common neoplasms in ferrets. Palpable nodules in the pancreas may indicate insulinoma. The pancreas has two limbs: the right limb lies along the descending duodenum, and the left limb extends toward the spleen and stomach.



Ferret pancreas showing the right limb, left limb, stomach, spleen, and duodenum.

Evaluate mesenteric lymph nodes -- mesenteric lymph nodes are large even in health, especially at the mesenteric root. They can be mistaken for a lesion! Do not confuse normal large lymph nodes with pathology.

Male urogenital anatomy: Evaluate the bladder, prostate, os penis, and urethral opening. The most common emergency presentation is urinary blockage. Name two etiologies for this (adrenal disease causing prostatic enlargement, and urolithiasis). A tube cystotomy can sometimes be necessary to provide urinary relief.

Female urogenital anatomy: Evaluate the uterus, ovaries, and vulva. Vulvar swelling can be a sign of adrenal disease or ovarian remnant syndrome in spayed ferrets.



Ferret Viscera

Left: Ventral aspect of the viscera of a ferret in situ. Right: Anatomy of the viscera and most important blood vessels as seen after removal of the lungs, liver, and gastrointestinal tract.

lab1/guinea-pig.html.title: Guinea Pig Anatomy
lab1/guinea-pig.html.body:
Guinea Pig Anatomy
Head Prosection

3D rendering of the guinea pig head showing the skull and dental anatomy.

Evaluate the palatal ostium to identify why it is difficult to intubate these species. The palatal ostium is the narrow opening in the soft palate that connects the oral cavity to the oropharynx -- its small size makes endotracheal intubation extremely challenging.

Observe the thick tongue base and angle of the teeth compared to the rabbit -- why is this important? The thick tongue base combined with the steep angle of the cheek teeth further limits visualization and access to the oropharynx.

Small nasal cavity and its relationship to maxillary teeth. The nasal passages are narrow and closely associated with the apices of the maxillary cheek teeth, meaning dental disease can lead to secondary nasal pathology.

Identify location of orbit and relationship to maxillary teeth. The orbit is closely associated with the apices of the maxillary premolar and molar teeth. Tooth root elongation or abscessation can cause retrobulbar disease and exophthalmos.



Carcass Prosection

Evaluate the small thoracic cavity and thoracic contents in situ. Guinea pigs have a remarkably small thoracic cavity relative to their abdominal cavity.

Relationship of GI tract to rest of abdomen. The GI tract, particularly the large cecum, dominates the abdominal cavity.

Evaluate the position and size of the cecum to consider the additional challenges of an abdominal incision in this species. The cecum occupies a very large portion of the abdomen and must be carefully managed during surgery.

Evaluate the size and thickness of the bladder. Compare with the rabbit -- the guinea pig bladder wall is thicker.

Evaluate the male coccygeal (grease) gland and the perineal sacs (also called perianal sacs). The grease gland on the dorsal rump produces oily secretions used for scent marking and can become impacted.

Evaluate the gastrointestinal tract -- guinea pigs are hindgut fermenters. The stomach is thin-walled and entirely lined with glandular mucosa (no non-glandular region). The cecum is very large, thin-walled, and occupies a significant portion of the abdominal cavity. The cecum has taeniae (longitudinal smooth muscle bands) and haustra (sacculations). The colon also has taeniae.

Evaluate the male reproductive anatomy -- guinea pigs have several unique features:

Open inguinal rings: The inguinal canals remain open throughout life. This is important surgically -- the inguinal rings must be closed during castration to prevent herniation of abdominal contents.

External testicular bursa: A large peritoneal fat pad (epididymal fat pad) is associated with the testicle and lies within the scrotal sac.

Accessory sex glands: Guinea pigs have large, prominent accessory sex glands including the seminal vesicles (vesicular glands), coagulating glands, prostate, and bulbourethral glands. The vesicular glands are particularly large and conspicuous.

Intromittent sac: A unique pouch ventral to the os penis that can accumulate debris and secretions. This sac can become impacted, especially in older boars, and requires periodic cleaning.

Os penis: A small bone is present within the glans penis.





Figure 3. Guinea pig male reproductive anatomy showing the accessory sex glands and associated structures.
Male Reproductive Anatomy Details

Fig 1. External testicular bursa. Note the large epididymal fat pad associated with the testis within the scrotal sac.

Fig 2. Guinea pig testicles and open inguinal rings. The open inguinal canals are clinically significant -- they must be closed during castration to prevent inguinal herniation.

Fig 3. Guinea pig vesicular glands (seminal vesicles). These accessory sex glands are remarkably large in the guinea pig and should not be mistaken for pathology.

Evaluate the glans penis -- the guinea pig glans penis has two lateral horns (cornua) and a prominent intromittent sac ventral to the os penis. The intromittent sac is a blind pouch that can accumulate keratinized debris, sebaceous secretions, and hair ("boar plug"). This accumulation requires periodic cleaning, especially in older males.


Illustration of the guinea pig glans penis showing the intromittent sac, os penis, and lateral horns (cornua). The intromittent sac is located ventral to the urethra.

Female Reproductive Anatomy

Evaluate the female external genitalia -- the female guinea pig has a Y-shaped vulvar opening with a vaginal closure membrane that seals the vaginal orifice except during estrus and parturition. The urethral papilla is located ventral to the vaginal opening within the vulvar area.


Illustration of the guinea pig female external genitalia showing the Y-shaped vulvar opening and urethral papilla.

Evaluate the female gonads and reproductive tract -- guinea pigs have a short duplex uterus with two separate uterine horns that each open independently into the vaginal canal via their own cervix. The ovaries are located caudal to the kidneys, partially enclosed by the ovarian bursa.


Figure 1. Guinea pig ovaries and reproductive tract in situ, showing the duplex uterus and ovarian position.

The urethral opening is extravaginal, like in all rodents. This is an important anatomical distinction from rabbits and other species.

Evaluate the ovaries for cystic disease -- ovarian cysts are extremely common in guinea pigs, with prevalence increasing with age. Cysts can be follicular (functional) or serous (rete ovarii cysts). They can become very large and may cause bilateral symmetric alopecia, abdominal distension, and discomfort. Ovariohysterectomy is the definitive treatment, though percutaneous drainage or hormonal therapy (e.g., GnRH agonists) can be used for non-surgical management.



Guinea pig ovarian cystic disease. Note the markedly enlarged, fluid-filled ovarian cysts. This is one of the most common reproductive disorders in guinea pigs.

References: Quesenberry KE, Mans C, Orcutt C, Carpenter JW. Ferrets, Rabbits, and Rodents: Clinical Medicine and Surgery. 4th ed. St. Louis: Elsevier; 2021.

lab1/rat.html.title: Rat Anatomy
lab1/rat.html.body:
Rat and Mouse Anatomy
Rat Prosection

Evaluate the gastrointestinal tract and compare with the other species -- the rat is an omnivore with a GI tract reflecting this dietary flexibility. The stomach is divided into two compartments by the limiting ridge (margo plicatus): a non-glandular forestomach (pars proventricularis) and a glandular stomach (pars glandularis). The non-glandular portion is lined with keratinized squamous epithelium and serves as a storage compartment, while the glandular portion contains gastric glands for enzymatic digestion. The cecum is large and well-developed, reflecting the capacity for hindgut fermentation.
Important: Rats (and mice) cannot vomit due to the anatomy of the limiting ridge, the relative strength of the crural sling of the diaphragm, and the lack of a brainstem emetic reflex. This has clinical implications for anesthetic protocols and toxin ingestion.



Rat stomach showing the limiting ridge (margo plicatus) that divides the non-glandular forestomach from the glandular stomach. The limiting ridge is the prominent mucosal fold separating the two compartments.

Evaluate the oral cavity -- note the prominent diastema between the incisors and molars (no canine or premolar teeth in rats). The dental formula is 1/1, 0/0, 0/0, 3/3 = 16 teeth. The incisors are open-rooted (aradicular hypsodont) and grow continuously, while the molars are rooted (anelodont) and do not grow continuously. Note the infolding of the lips into the diastema, which separates the oral cavity into an anterior and posterior compartment. This prevents ingestion of non-food material while gnawing.

Evaluate the harderian gland -- located behind the eye, this gland produces porphyrin-rich secretions (red-brown pigment). Excessive porphyrin secretion (chromodacryorrhea or "red tears") is a sign of stress, illness, or pain. It is distributed over the fur during grooming and can be mistaken for blood.

Evaluate the male reproductive tract -- the rat has large, prominent testes relative to body size. The inguinal canals remain open throughout life (open inguinal rings), allowing the testes to move freely between the scrotal and abdominal positions. As with the guinea pig, the open inguinal rings must be closed during castration.
Male accessory sex organs include the seminal vesicles (very large, paired, coiled tubular glands), coagulating glands (anterior prostate), ventral prostate, dorsolateral prostate, and bulbourethral glands. The seminal vesicles and coagulating glands produce secretions that form a copulatory plug in the female vagina after mating. The preputial glands produce pheromones and can become impacted or develop abscesses. The os penis is present.

Evaluate the female reproductive tract -- the rat has a duplex uterus with two completely separate uterine horns, each with its own cervix opening into a common vagina. The ovaries are enclosed within an ovarian bursa. Mammary tissue is extensive and distributed widely across the body.



Figure 4. Rat female reproductive organs showing the duplex uterus with two uterine horns and associated structures.

Evaluate the mammary gland distribution -- mammary tissue in the rat is extensive, extending from the cervical region (near the salivary glands) to the inguinal region. There are typically 6 pairs of mammary glands: 3 thoracic (cervical, thoracic cranial, thoracic caudal) and 3 abdominal/inguinal (abdominal cranial, abdominal caudal, inguinal). Mammary tumors are among the most common neoplasms in rats, particularly in females. Fibroadenomas are the most common type in rats and are often benign, but can grow very large.


Diagram showing the distribution of mammary tissue in the rat. Note the extensive area of mammary tissue extending from the cervical to the inguinal region.

Mammary gland distribution in the rat shown on a dark background, highlighting the widespread nature of the mammary tissue across the ventral body wall.

Evaluate the thoracic and abdominal organs -- note the thymus, which persists into adulthood in the rat (unlike many other species). The spleen is a long, flat, tongue-shaped organ.


Mouse Anatomy
The mouse shares many anatomical features with the rat. The following images illustrate key features of mouse anatomy for comparison.

Figure 1. Mouse abdominal and thoracic organs in situ. Note the similar organ arrangement to the rat but at a smaller scale.
Mouse Male Reproductive System

Diagram of the mouse male reproductive system showing the testes, epididymis, vas deferens, seminal vesicles, coagulating glands, prostate, and bulbourethral glands. The anatomy is similar to the rat with large seminal vesicles and open inguinal canals.

References: Quesenberry KE, Mans C, Orcutt C, Carpenter JW. Ferrets, Rabbits, and Rodents: Clinical Medicine and Surgery. 4th ed. St. Louis: Elsevier; 2021. Percy DH, Barthold SW. Pathology of Laboratory Rodents and Rabbits. 4th ed. Ames: Wiley-Blackwell; 2016.

lab1/rabbit.html.title: Rabbit Anatomy
lab1/rabbit.html.body:
Rabbit Anatomy
Head -- Sagittal Section
Evaluate the sagittal section of the rabbit head and identify the following structures:
a. Soft palate -- the soft palate is long and extends caudally, effectively separating the oral cavity from the pharynx. The rabbit is an obligate nasal breather. The epiglottis is engaged dorsal to the soft palate, creating a continuous airway from the nasal cavity to the trachea. This anatomy makes orotracheal intubation challenging, as the tube must be passed blindly around the base of the tongue and past the soft palate.
b. Tongue -- the tongue is large and fleshy, and the torus linguae (a prominent dorsal elevation at the base of the tongue) further limits oropharyngeal visualization. This is another reason why intubation is difficult.
c. Nasal cavity -- the nasal cavity is long and narrow with extensive scrolling of the turbinate bones (maxilloturbinates and ethmoturbinates), providing a large surface area for air conditioning and olfaction. The nasal passages are important in thermoregulation. Pasteurella multocida and other bacteria commonly colonize the nasal cavity, contributing to upper respiratory disease ("snuffles").
d. Nasolacrimal duct -- the nasolacrimal duct follows a tortuous course from the medial canthus of the eye, through the maxillary bone (passing close to the roots of the upper incisor and premolar teeth), and opens at the mucocutaneous junction of the nostril (alar fold). The proximity of the duct to the tooth roots means that dental disease (particularly incisor or premolar root elongation or abscessation) can compress or obstruct the nasolacrimal duct, causing epiphora (excessive tearing) and secondary dacryocystitis.
e. Brain -- note the relatively small brain size relative to the skull. The skull is composed of thin, fragile bones, and the large orbits are separated by only a thin bony septum.

Larynx
The rabbit larynx is small and difficult to visualize due to the anatomy of the oral cavity (small oral opening, large tongue, long soft palate). The following images show the larynx in closed and open positions.

Rabbit larynx in the closed position. Note the small size and the position relative to the soft palate.

Rabbit larynx in the open position. Visualization of the laryngeal opening is essential for endotracheal intubation, which is one of the most challenging aspects of rabbit anesthesia.

Thoracic Organs
Thymus
The thymus in the rabbit is large and persists into adulthood, unlike in many domestic species. It occupies the cranial mediastinum ventral to the trachea and great vessels. The thymus can be visible on thoracic radiographs and should not be mistaken for a mediastinal mass.

Rabbit thoracic anatomy showing the thymus and associated structures.

Right caudal lobe of the lung

Left caudal lobe of the lung
Left cranial lobe of the lung (caudal part)
Left cranial lobe of the lung (cranial part)

Right external jugular vein

Aortic arch

Heart and Great Vessels
The rabbit heart is relatively small compared to body size. The aortic arch gives rise to the brachiocephalic trunk and left subclavian artery. The brachiocephalic trunk divides into the right subclavian artery and a common trunk for both common carotid arteries.

Abdominal Contents
Liver
The rabbit liver is large and multilobed. It is important to identify the individual lobes, as hepatic lobe torsion (particularly of the caudate lobe) is a recognized clinical condition in rabbits.

Rabbit liver showing the multiple hepatic lobes. The liver is large relative to body size.
Hepatic lobe abbreviations:

RLL -- Right lateral lobe
RML -- Right medial lobe
QF -- Quadrate fossa (quadrate lobe)
LML -- Left medial lobe
LLL -- Left lateral lobe
CL -- Caudate lobe (caudate process)
PPC -- Papillary process of the caudate lobe
GB -- Gallbladder

The gallbladder lies between the right medial lobe and the quadrate lobe. The caudate lobe has both a caudate process (extending toward the right kidney) and a papillary process (extending toward the lesser curvature of the stomach).
Gastrointestinal Tract
The rabbit is a hindgut fermenter with a highly specialized large intestine. The stomach is simple and thin-walled. The small intestine (duodenum, jejunum, ileum) is relatively short compared to the large intestine. The sacculus rotundus (ileocecal tonsil) is a spherical lymphoid organ at the ileocecal junction, unique to rabbits.
Large Intestine
The cecum is the largest organ in the abdominal cavity, accounting for approximately 40% of the total GI tract volume. It is a large, thin-walled, coiled structure with a blind-ending appendix (vermiform appendix) at its tip. The appendix is rich in lymphoid tissue. The cecum is the site of microbial fermentation.
The colon is divided into the proximal colon (with the fusus coli, a pacemaker region that regulates the separation of digestible and indigestible fiber fractions) and the distal colon.

Rabbit large intestine dissected to show the cecum, appendix, and colonic structures.
Key:

Sacculus rotundus (ileocecal tonsil)
Cecum (body)
Cecal appendix (vermiform appendix)
Ampulla caecalis coli (proximal colon origin)
Proximal colon (with haustra/sacculations)
Fusus coli
Distal colon
Rectum

The fusus coli is a thickened, darkly pigmented region of the proximal colon that acts as a pacemaker, controlling colonic motility. It is responsible for the separation mechanism that sorts fine digestible particles (which are retropelled back into the cecum for fermentation) from coarse indigestible fiber (which passes distally to be excreted as hard fecal pellets). This mechanism underlies cecotrophy -- the production and ingestion of cecotropes (soft, mucus-coated fecal pellets rich in vitamins, volatile fatty acids, and microbial protein).

Urogenital System
Male Urogenital Anatomy

Illustration of the rabbit male urogenital anatomy showing the relationship between the reproductive and urinary structures.
The male rabbit has several notable features:

Testes: The rabbit has large, elongated testes that lie in hairless scrotal sacs located craniolateral to the penis (an unusual position compared to most mammals). The inguinal canals remain open (open inguinal rings), and the testes can be retracted into the abdomen.

Accessory sex glands: Include the vesicular gland (seminal vesicle), prostate gland, and bulbourethral gland (paraprostate).

Inguinal glands: Scent glands located in hairless pouches lateral to the genitalia. These produce a waxy, pheromone-rich secretion used for territorial marking. They can become impacted and require cleaning.



Rabbit scrotal and testicular dissection showing the open inguinal ring and the position of the testes in the scrotal sacs.

Detailed illustration of the rabbit male urogenital anatomy.

Ductus deferens (vas deferens)

Prostate gland
Bulbourethral gland (paraprostate)
Inguinal gland

Female Urogenital Anatomy
The female rabbit has a duplex uterus (uterus duplex) -- two completely separate uterine horns, each with its own cervix that opens independently into the vagina. There is no uterine body. This anatomy is important for surgical planning during ovariohysterectomy, as the surgeon must ligate each uterine horn separately at the level of each cervix.
Rabbits are induced ovulators -- ovulation occurs approximately 10-12 hours after mating, triggered by the coital stimulus. The ovaries are located caudal to the kidneys.

Rabbit female reproductive tract showing the duplex uterus with two separate uterine horns and cervices, and the ovaries.
Uterine adenocarcinoma is one of the most common neoplasms in intact female rabbits, with prevalence increasing significantly with age (up to 60-80% in some breeds by 4-6 years of age). This is a primary indication for elective ovariohysterectomy in pet rabbits.

Paranasal Cavities
The rabbit has extensive and complex paranasal sinuses and nasal cavities. The turbinate bones are highly scrolled, providing a large surface area. The maxillary recess is located lateral to the nasal cavity and is closely associated with the roots of the premolar and molar teeth.

A. Illustration of the rabbit paranasal cavities showing the complex arrangement of turbinate bones and sinuses.

B. Photograph of a rabbit skull sectioned to show the paranasal cavities and the relationship between the nasal passages and the dental arcades.
The close association between the tooth roots and the nasal cavity/sinuses explains why dental disease in rabbits frequently leads to secondary rhinitis, dacryocystitis, and retrobulbar abscesses. Periapical infections of the upper cheek teeth can extend into the nasal cavity or orbit.

References: Varga M. Textbook of Rabbit Medicine. 2nd ed. Oxford: Butterworth-Heinemann; 2014. Quesenberry KE, Mans C, Orcutt C, Carpenter JW. Ferrets, Rabbits, and Rodents: Clinical Medicine and Surgery. 4th ed. St. Louis: Elsevier; 2021.

lab2/.title: Lab 2: Physical Examination and Clinical Techniques
lab2/.body:
Lab 2: Physical Examination and Clinical Techniques
VET-436 / 2025
Hugues Beaufrere, Michelle Hawkins, Krista Keller, David Guzman, Ariella Darvish, Marina Liles

In this lab, you will practice handling rabbits, performing a complete rabbit physical examination, and practicing a few important clinical techniques including venipuncture, subcutaneous injections, and nasolacrimal duct flushing.
Please review the videos in the lab module prior to the lab.
Rabbits have been sedated with midazolam.

lab2/outcomes.html.title: Learning Outcomes
lab2/outcomes.html.body:
Learning Outcomes

Perform a thorough physical examination of a rabbit including full oral and aural examinations.
Identify two different intramuscular injection sites for use in the rabbit.
Identify no less than 3 potential venipuncture sites for use in the rabbit.
Identify sites for subcutaneous injection for use in the rabbit.
Perform venipuncture from the lateral saphenous vein.
Perform nasolacrimal duct flush and determine duct patency.
Perform safe restraint and handling of rabbits.

lab2/handling.html.title: Handling and Restraint
lab2/handling.html.body:
Handling and Restraint
Distant Examination
Before handling the rabbit, take a moment to observe the patient from a distance. Note the following:

Mentation and behavior: Is the rabbit alert, depressed, or lethargic? Is it interacting with its environment?
Posture: Is the rabbit sitting normally, hunched, or pressing its head into a corner?
Respiratory rate and effort: Count the respiratory rate before handling. Normal respiratory rate is 30-60 breaths per minute. Note any increased effort, open-mouth breathing, or nasal flaring.
Body condition: Does the rabbit appear thin, overweight, or normal?
Gait and mobility: If the rabbit is moving, does it appear coordinated? Is there any lameness?
Any discharges: Observe for nasal discharge, ocular discharge, or soiling around the perineum.

Rabbit Grimace Scale
The Rabbit Grimace Scale (RbtGS) is a validated tool for assessing pain in rabbits. It evaluates five facial action units, each scored from 0 (not present) to 2 (obviously present):

Orbital tightening: Closing of the eyelid (narrowing of orbital area). A wrinkle may be visible around the eye.
Cheek flattening: Flattening of the cheeks. When obviously present, cheeks have a sunken look. The face becomes more angular and less rounded.
Nostril shape: Nostrils (nares) are drawn vertically forming a "V" rather than "U" shape. Nose tip is moved down towards the chin.
Whisker shape and position: Whiskers are pushed away from the face to stand on end. Whiskers stiffen and lose their natural, downward curve. Whiskers increasingly point in the same direction. When obviously present, whiskers move downwards.
Ear shape and position: Ears become more tightly folded/curled (more cylindrical) in shape. Ears rotate from facing towards the source of sound to facing towards the hindquarters. Ears may be held closer to the back or sides of the body.


  
  The Rabbit Grimace Scale (RbtGS). Five facial action units are each scored from 0 (not present) to 2 (obviously present) to assess pain in rabbits.



Safety Warnings

IMPORTANT SAFETY PRECAUTIONS

NEVER pick up a rabbit by its ears. This is painful and can cause injury.
NEVER place a rabbit on its back (trance/tonic immobility). This is a fear response, not relaxation, and is extremely stressful.
ALWAYS support the hindquarters. Rabbits have powerful hind legs and a relatively fragile spine. If a rabbit kicks out while unsupported, it can fracture its lumbar spine, resulting in paralysis.
Be aware that rabbits can scratch with their hind claws and bite when frightened.
Work on a non-slip surface (e.g., a towel on the exam table) to prevent the rabbit from slipping and panicking.
Keep the environment quiet and calm. Rabbits are prey animals and are easily stressed by loud noises and sudden movements.



Removing from the Cage

Open the cage door and allow the rabbit to come out on its own if possible.
If the rabbit must be removed, reach in and place one hand under the thorax and one hand supporting the hindquarters.
Slide the rabbit towards you and lift it out, keeping it close to your body.
Never pull a rabbit out by the scruff alone or by the ears.
For top-opening cages, reach in with both hands, scoop the rabbit up from underneath, and lift straight up while supporting the hindquarters.


Football Hold
The football hold is one of the most common and secure ways to carry a rabbit. The rabbit is held firmly against the handler's body, similar to how one would carry a football.

Tuck the rabbit's head into the crook of your elbow (the antecubital fossa).
Support the body along your forearm.
Use your hand to firmly support the hindquarters.
The rabbit's body should be pressed against your side/torso for security.
Your other hand can be placed over the rabbit's back for additional stability.
This hold keeps the rabbit's eyes covered, which has a calming effect.


  
  The football hold: the rabbit is tucked against the handler's body with the head in the crook of the elbow and the hindquarters firmly supported.



Calming with a Towel

Placing a towel over the rabbit's eyes can have a calming effect, as it reduces visual stimulation.
A towel draped over the rabbit on the exam table can help keep the rabbit still during examination.
The towel also provides a non-slip surface for the rabbit's feet.


Towel Restraint (Burrito Technique)
The towel burrito (also called towel wrap or burrito wrap) is an excellent restraint technique for rabbits that are fractious or for procedures that require the rabbit to remain still (e.g., blood draws, nasolacrimal duct flushes, oral examinations).
Steps:

Place the rabbit on a large towel on the exam table.
Gather the towel snugly around the rabbit's neck, being careful not to restrict breathing.
Wrap one side of the towel over the rabbit's body and tuck it under.
Wrap the other side over and tuck it under as well.
The rabbit should be snugly wrapped with only its head exposed.
Individual limbs can be exposed as needed for procedures by creating small openings in the wrap.


  
  Step-by-step diagram illustrating how to burrito wrap a rabbit for safe restraint.



  
  A rabbit restrained using the towel burrito technique, with only the head exposed.



Putting the Rabbit Back in the Cage

Always place the rabbit hind end first into the cage or carrier.
If you place the rabbit head first, it may kick backwards with its powerful hind legs, potentially injuring itself or the handler.
Support the rabbit securely as you lower it into the cage.
Place the rabbit gently on the floor of the cage and release your hold only once the rabbit is settled.
Ensure the cage door is secured after placing the rabbit inside.

lab2/physical-exam.html.title: Physical Examination Checklist
lab2/physical-exam.html.body:
Physical Examination Checklist
What You Need to Bring

Stethoscope
Penlight
Notepad and pen for recording findings
Watch or timer (for heart rate and respiratory rate)

The following otoscope and oral speculum will be provided:

Otoscope with small (2-3 mm) cone attachment
Oral speculum or cheek dilators for dental examination


Body Weight and Body Condition Score

Weigh the rabbit in kilograms using a gram scale.
Assign a body condition score (BCS) on a scale of 1-5:
1 - Very Thin: Hip bones, ribs, and spine are very sharp to the touch. Loss of muscle and no fat cover. The rump area curves in.
2 - Thin: Hip bones, ribs, and spine are easily felt. Loss of muscle and very little fat cover. Rump area is flat.
3 - Ideal: Hip bones, ribs, and spine easily felt but are rounded, not sharp. Ribs feel like a pocket full of pens. No abdominal bulge. Rump area is flat.
4 - Overweight: Pressure is needed to feel the ribs, spine, and hip bones. Some fat layers. The rump is rounded.
5 - Obese: Very hard to feel the spine and hip bones. Ribs cannot be felt. Tummy sags with obvious fat padding. Rump bulges out.




  
  Rabbit body condition scoring chart (scale 1-5). An ideal body condition score is 3.



Skin Turgor (Hydration Status)

Gently tent the skin over the interscapular area (between the shoulder blades).
Normal skin should return to its resting position within 1-2 seconds.
Prolonged skin tenting suggests dehydration.
Note: Obese rabbits may have normal skin turgor even when dehydrated due to excess subcutaneous fat. Thin rabbits may have prolonged skin turgor even when normally hydrated.


Cardiovascular System

Auscultate the heart on both sides of the thorax using your stethoscope.
Normal heart rate (HR): 140-180 bpm (may be up to 220-325 bpm when stressed).
Note the rate, rhythm, and character of the heart sounds.
Listen for any murmurs, arrhythmias, or muffled heart sounds.
Evaluate mucous membrane color: should be pink. Pale, cyanotic, or hyperemic membranes are abnormal.
Assess capillary refill time (CRT): should be less than 2 seconds.
Palpate peripheral pulses (central ear artery).


NOTE: The rabbits have been sedated with midazolam. Sedation may affect heart rate, respiratory rate, and mentation. Keep this in mind when interpreting your examination findings. Some procedures such as otoscopic and oral examinations are very challenging to perform on awake rabbits and are best done under sedation.


Otoscopic Examination

Use an otoscope with a small cone (2-3 mm) to examine both ear canals and tympanic membranes.
Gently restrain the rabbit. Sedation or the burrito technique may be helpful.
Hold the pinna (ear) gently and direct the otoscope cone into the vertical ear canal.
Evaluate the ear canal for:
Erythema (redness)
Discharge (ceruminous, purulent, or hemorrhagic)
Debris or foreign material
Masses or polyps
Parasites (e.g., Psoroptes cuniculi - ear mites)


Visualize the tympanic membrane if possible. It should be intact, translucent, and pearly grey.
Note that rabbit ear canals have a significant vertical and horizontal component.
In lop-eared breeds, the ear canal may be more tortuous and difficult to examine.


  
  Otoscopic examination of a rabbit ear using an otoscope with a small cone attachment.



Dental and Oral Examination

Rabbits are elodont (continuously growing teeth) with a dental formula of I2/1, C0/0, P3/2, M3/3 = 28 teeth.
The small peg teeth (second upper incisors) are located directly behind the upper primary incisors.
Evaluate the incisors by gently retracting the lips:
Check for malocclusion, overgrowth, fractures, or discoloration.
Upper incisors should slightly overlap the lower incisors.
Look for the peg teeth behind the upper incisors.


Evaluate the cheek teeth (premolars and molars) using an otoscope or oral speculum/cheek dilators:
This is best performed under sedation.
Insert the speculum or cheek dilators gently between the incisors and premolars (the diastema).
Use a light source to illuminate the oral cavity.
Evaluate for molar spurs (sharp points), especially on the buccal aspect of upper cheek teeth and the lingual aspect of lower cheek teeth.
Look for tongue entrapment by lingual spurs of the lower cheek teeth.
Assess for oral ulceration, abscesses, or mucosal lesions.
Note any purulent material or food impaction.


Palpate the ventral mandible for any swelling or irregularity that may indicate tooth root abscessation or elongation.


  
  Oral examination of a rabbit using cheek dilators to visualize the cheek teeth. Note the view of the incisors and premolars.



Remaining Physical Examination
Lymph Nodes

Palpate the submandibular lymph nodes.
Palpate the prescapular lymph nodes.
Palpate the axillary lymph nodes.
Palpate the inguinal lymph nodes.
Palpate the popliteal lymph nodes.
Note any enlargement, asymmetry, firmness, or pain on palpation.

Dewlap

The dewlap is a fold of skin and subcutaneous fat under the chin, particularly prominent in intact female rabbits and obese rabbits.
Inspect the dewlap for moist dermatitis (dewlap dermatitis or "wet dewlap"), which occurs when the skin fold remains chronically moist.
Note any alopecia, erythema, discharge, or odor.

Masses

Palpate the entire body systematically for any subcutaneous masses, swellings, or abscesses.
Rabbit abscesses are typically encapsulated and contain thick, caseous (cottage cheese-like) pus, unlike the liquid pus seen in dogs and cats.
Note the location, size, shape, consistency, and mobility of any masses found.


Upper Respiratory System

Observe the nares (nostrils) for any discharge (serous, mucoid, or purulent).
Note any sneezing, nasal congestion, or stertor (upper airway noise).
Evaluate for matting of the fur on the medial forelimbs, which indicates the rabbit has been wiping nasal discharge with its paws.
Common causes of upper respiratory disease in rabbits include Pasteurella multocida, Bordetella bronchiseptica, Staphylococcus aureus, and dental disease.


Ocular Examination

Evaluate both eyes for:
Symmetry of the globes.
Discharge (serous, mucoid, or purulent). Epiphora (excessive tearing) may indicate nasolacrimal duct obstruction.
Conjunctival hyperemia or chemosis.
Corneal clarity: Evaluate for ulcers, opacities, or neovascularization using a penlight.
Pupil size and symmetry: Evaluate pupillary light reflexes (PLR) - note that rabbits have a relatively slow and incomplete PLR.
Lens: Look for cataracts (lens opacity). Encephalitozoon cuniculi can cause phacoclastic uveitis.
Third eyelid: Evaluate the nictitating membrane for protrusion or abnormalities.
Periorbital region: Palpate for retrobulbar swelling or exophthalmos, which may indicate retrobulbar abscess (commonly associated with tooth root elongation).


Perform retropulsion of the globes: Gently push each globe posteriorly through the closed eyelids to evaluate for retrobulbar masses or abscesses. Compare both sides. Resistance to retropulsion or asymmetry suggests retrobulbar disease.


  
  Performing retropulsion of the globe. Gently push the globe posteriorly through the closed eyelid to assess for retrobulbar disease.



Lower Respiratory System

Normal respiratory rate (RR): 30-60 breaths per minute.
Auscultate both sides of the thorax for lung sounds.
Normal rabbits are obligate nasal breathers. Open-mouth breathing is a sign of severe respiratory distress.
Evaluate for:
Increased respiratory rate (tachypnea).
Increased respiratory effort (dyspnea) - look for abdominal component, nostril flaring, head extension.
Abnormal lung sounds: crackles, wheezes, or areas of decreased/absent sounds.
Referred upper airway sounds can be transmitted to the thorax, so always auscultate the trachea as well.




Abdomen

Abdominal palpation is an essential component of the rabbit physical examination. Rabbits are relatively easy to palpate due to their lack of a large omentum.
Place the rabbit on the exam table on a non-slip surface.
Use both hands to gently palpate the abdomen systematically.

Stomach

The stomach is located in the left cranial abdomen, tucked under the rib cage.
The stomach should always contain some ingesta (food material). An empty stomach is abnormal and may suggest anorexia or GI stasis.
Assess the stomach for size, consistency, and the presence of gas or fluid.
A doughy, large stomach may suggest GI stasis. A tympanic (gas-filled) stomach is an emergency.

Cecum

The cecum is the largest organ in the rabbit abdomen and is located in the ventral and right abdomen.
It should feel like a soft, doughy, tubular structure.
Assess for distension, gas, or impaction.

Intestines

Palpate for intestinal loops. They should be soft and non-painful.
Note any thickening, distension, masses, or gas.
Small intestinal loops should be mobile and non-tender.

Kidneys

The left kidney is more caudal and mobile than the right kidney.
The right kidney is more cranial and partially tucked under the rib cage.
Palpate both kidneys for size, shape, symmetry, and pain.
Normal kidneys should be smooth and bean-shaped.

Bladder

The urinary bladder is located in the caudal ventral abdomen.
Assess for size and distension.
Note: Rabbit urine is normally thick and creamy due to high calcium carbonate content. A palpably large or firm bladder may indicate urinary sludge or urolithiasis.

Liver

The liver is in the cranial abdomen, mostly under the rib cage.
It is generally not palpable unless enlarged (hepatomegaly).


  
  Abdominal palpation of a rabbit. Use both hands to systematically evaluate the abdominal organs.



Urogenital Examination
Female

Evaluate the vulva for discharge, swelling, or discoloration.
Palpate the uterus if possible (located in the caudal ventral abdomen). A large or palpable uterus may suggest pregnancy, pyometra, or uterine neoplasia.
Note: Uterine adenocarcinoma is extremely common in intact female rabbits over 3-4 years of age (incidence up to 60-80% by 5-6 years).
Check the mammary glands for swelling, masses, or discharge (mammary neoplasia can occur).
The inguinal glands (located in the inguinal skin folds lateral to the genitalia) should be evaluated. These are scent glands that can accumulate waxy secretions and debris. Clean if needed.

Male

Evaluate the prepuce and penis by gently extruding the penis from the prepuce.
The testicles should be palpated in the inguinal region. Male rabbits have open inguinal rings and can retract their testicles into the abdomen.
Note any testicular asymmetry, swelling, or masses.
The inguinal glands should be evaluated as in the female.


  
  Rabbit held in dorsal position for urogenital examination. Note the inguinal region and perineal area.



Feet Examination

Examine all four feet, paying particular attention to the plantar surface (soles) of the hind feet.
Rabbits do not have footpads like dogs and cats. Instead, the plantar surface is covered with dense fur.
Evaluate for pododermatitis (sore hocks / ulcerative pododermatitis):
Early stages: fur loss and callus formation on the plantar metatarsal area.
Advanced stages: ulceration, erythema, swelling, scab formation, and secondary infection.
Severe cases can progress to osteomyelitis.


Risk factors for pododermatitis include obesity, wire-bottom cages, inadequate bedding, wet/soiled substrate, inactivity, and Rex breeds (thinner foot fur).
Evaluate the nails for overgrowth, fractures, or abnormalities. Trim if needed.


  
  Examination of the plantar surface of a rabbit's hind feet. Evaluate for pododermatitis (sore hocks).



Brief Neurological Examination

Assess mentation: alert, quiet, depressed, obtunded, stuporous, or comatose (keep sedation in mind).
Evaluate gait and posture: ataxia, paresis, head tilt, circling, or rolling.
Head tilt (torticollis/vestibular disease) is common in rabbits and can be caused by Encephalitozoon cuniculi (protozoal infection) or Pasteurella multocida (otitis media/interna).
Assess postural reactions (proprioception) by turning the paw over (knuckling) on each limb.
Evaluate cranial nerve function:
Menace response (CN II, VII) - note that this can be inconsistent in rabbits.
Pupillary light reflex (CN II, III).
Palpebral reflex (CN V, VII).
Physiologic nystagmus (CN VIII) - slow, horizontal nystagmus can be normal.


Note any nystagmus (pathological): direction, type (horizontal, vertical, rotary), and whether it is spontaneous or positional.
Assess muscle tone and withdrawal reflexes in all four limbs.
Evaluate the perineal reflex (anal tone).


Rectal Temperature

Normal rectal temperature: 101-104°F (38.3-40°C).
Use a digital thermometer with lubricant.
Gently insert the thermometer into the rectum approximately 2-3 cm.
Note: Rabbits are prone to hyperthermia (heat stress) at environmental temperatures above 85°F (29°C). They cannot pant or sweat effectively and rely on vasodilation of their ear pinnae for thermoregulation.
Hypothermia may be seen in severely ill, debilitated, or shocked rabbits.

lab2/procedures.html.title: Procedures
lab2/procedures.html.body:
Procedures
Nasolacrimal Duct Flush
The nasolacrimal duct in rabbits has a single punctum located on the lower eyelid (ventromedial conjunctival fornix), near the medial canthus. The duct follows a tortuous path through the maxilla, passing close to the root of the upper incisor and the maxillary premolars/molars before opening at the nasal punctum (at the mucocutaneous junction of the nostril). Because of its proximity to tooth roots, dental disease is a common cause of nasolacrimal duct obstruction.
Indications

Epiphora (excessive tearing) and dacryocystitis (infection/inflammation of the nasolacrimal duct).
Evaluation of nasolacrimal duct patency.
Therapeutic flushing to relieve obstruction from inspissated pus (commonly associated with Pasteurella multocida).

Equipment

24- or 26-gauge lacrimal cannula or intravenous catheter (without the stylet).
1 mL or 3 mL syringe.
Sterile saline (0.9% NaCl) for flushing.
Ophthalmic topical anesthetic (e.g., proparacaine 0.5%) - optional, can help with patient comfort.
Magnification (loupes) may be helpful.

Procedure

Sedate the rabbit if not already sedated. Restraint with the burrito technique may be sufficient in some cases.
Optionally, apply topical ophthalmic anesthetic (proparacaine) to the eye. Wait 30-60 seconds for it to take effect.
Identify the lower lacrimal punctum. It is located on the medial aspect of the lower eyelid, in the ventromedial conjunctival fornix, near the medial canthus. It may be difficult to visualize - gently evert the lower eyelid and look for a small opening.
Attach the lacrimal cannula (or IV catheter without stylet) to a syringe filled with sterile saline.
Gently insert the cannula into the lower punctum. Direct the cannula ventrally and nasally.
Slowly and gently flush sterile saline through the duct. Do not use excessive pressure.
If the duct is patent, saline will exit from the nasal punctum at the nostril. You may see fluid dripping from the nose.
If resistance is encountered, the duct may be obstructed. Do not force the flush. Gentle, pulsatile pressure may help dislodge small obstructions.
Note the character of any material that is flushed out (clear, mucoid, purulent). Purulent material is commonly associated with Pasteurella infection.
If indicated, culture any purulent material for bacterial culture and sensitivity.


  
  Nasolacrimal duct flush in a rabbit. The lacrimal cannula is inserted into the ventral (lower) lacrimal punctum near the medial canthus.



  
  Close-up of the lateral ear vein (marginal ear vein) of a rabbit, which can be used for venipuncture or catheter placement.



Injections
Intramuscular (IM) Injection Sites
Two primary intramuscular injection sites are used in rabbits:

Lumbar epaxial muscles (longissimus dorsi):

Located along either side of the lumbar spine.
This is the most commonly used IM injection site in rabbits.
Palpate the lumbar spine and inject into the muscle mass lateral to the dorsal spinous processes.
Use a 25-gauge needle.
Maximum volume: approximately 0.5-1 mL per site, depending on the size of the rabbit.


Quadriceps (cranial thigh) muscle:

Located on the cranial aspect of the thigh (cranial femoral muscles).
Palpate the femur and inject into the muscle mass on the cranial/lateral aspect.
Use a 25-gauge needle.
Maximum volume: approximately 0.5-1 mL per site.
Caution: Avoid the sciatic nerve, which runs along the caudal aspect of the femur. Always inject into the cranial or lateral thigh, not the caudal thigh.




NOTE: The caudal thigh muscles should be avoided due to the risk of sciatic nerve damage.

Subcutaneous (SC) Injection Sites

The interscapular region (scruff, between the shoulder blades) is the most commonly used site for subcutaneous injections and subcutaneous fluid administration.
Gently tent the skin over the interscapular area.
Insert a 22- to 25-gauge needle into the subcutaneous space at the base of the skin tent.
Inject the medication slowly.
The lateral thorax and lateral flank can also be used for subcutaneous injections.
Subcutaneous fluids can be given in volumes of 10-15 mL/kg per site in the interscapular region.


Venipuncture
Venous Access Sites
The following veins can be used for venipuncture (blood collection) or catheter placement in rabbits:

Marginal ear vein (lateral ear vein):

Located on the lateral aspect of the pinna.
Useful for small blood sample collection and IV catheter placement.
Apply topical EMLA cream (lidocaine/prilocaine) 30-60 minutes prior, or use a local lidocaine bleb to reduce pain.
Use a 25- or 27-gauge needle or butterfly catheter.
Avoid the central ear artery (located on the dorsal midline of the pinna).


Central ear artery:

Located along the dorsal midline of the pinna.
Can be used for arterial blood gas sampling.
Not routinely used for venipuncture (it is an artery).
Apply pressure after sampling to prevent hematoma formation.


Lateral saphenous vein:

Located on the lateral aspect of the hind limb, crossing the lateral surface of the tarsus (hock).
This is an excellent site for blood collection in rabbits.
See detailed technique below.


Cephalic vein:

Located on the dorsal aspect of the forelimb, similar to dogs and cats.
Can be used for blood collection and IV catheter placement.
Clip the fur if needed to visualize the vein.


Jugular vein:

Located in the jugular groove, similar to dogs and cats.
Can be used for larger volume blood collection.
Requires good restraint or sedation.
The large dewlap in some rabbits may make this site more difficult to access.



Lateral Saphenous Vein Venipuncture: Detailed Technique
The lateral saphenous vein is the preferred venipuncture site for this lab.
Equipment:

25- or 27-gauge needle attached to a 1 mL or 3 mL syringe (or a 25-gauge butterfly catheter).
Alcohol or chlorhexidine for skin preparation.
Cotton ball or gauze for hemostasis.
Clippers (optional, to remove fur over the vein).

Procedure:

Restrain the rabbit appropriately. The rabbit can be placed on the table in sternal recumbency, or the burrito technique can be used with the hind limb exposed. An assistant should restrain the rabbit while the phlebotomist performs the blood draw.
Extend the hind limb caudally and laterally by gently grasping the leg above the hock.
Clip the fur over the lateral tarsus (hock region) if needed to visualize the vein. The lateral saphenous vein crosses the lateral surface of the hock.
The assistant should occlude the vein by applying gentle pressure proximal to the hock (above the sampling site), acting as a tourniquet. This can be done by gently wrapping the hand around the leg above the tarsus.
Prepare the skin with alcohol or chlorhexidine.
Identify the vein. The lateral saphenous vein should be visible or palpable crossing the lateral hock.
Insert the needle at a shallow angle (10-20 degrees) into the vein, with the bevel up.
Gently aspirate. Blood should flow into the syringe. If using a butterfly catheter, blood will appear in the tubing.
Collect the required blood volume. The safe blood collection volume is approximately 1% of body weight (e.g., 10 mL from a 1 kg rabbit, though in practice smaller volumes are typically collected). A more conservative maximum is 0.5-1 mL/100 g body weight.
Release the tourniquet (assistant releases pressure above the hock).
Remove the needle and immediately apply pressure with a cotton ball or gauze for at least 60 seconds to achieve hemostasis.
Transfer blood to the appropriate collection tubes (EDTA for CBC, lithium heparin or serum separator for chemistry).


Tips:

If blood flow stops, gently reposition the needle. The vein may have collapsed or the needle may have gone through the vein.
Warming the limb with a warm compress prior to venipuncture may help dilate the vein.
Use the smallest gauge needle appropriate for the sample volume needed.
Avoid excessive negative pressure on the syringe, as this can collapse the vein and hemolyze the sample.

lab2/appendix-a.html.title: Appendix A: Rabbit Characteristics
lab2/appendix-a.html.body:
Appendix A: Anatomical and Biological Characteristics of Rabbits
Integument

Thin, delicate skin that is easily torn. Care must be taken during handling, restraint, and any surgical procedures.
Dewlap: A fold of skin under the chin, more prominent in intact females and obese rabbits. Used for fur pulling to line the nest during pregnancy. Susceptible to moist dermatitis ("wet dewlap").
Scent glands:
Inguinal glands: Located in the inguinal skin folds lateral to the genitalia. Produce a brown, waxy, odorous secretion. Can accumulate debris and require periodic cleaning.
Chin gland (submandibular gland): Used for territorial marking ("chinning" behavior). Rabbits rub their chin on objects to deposit scent.


Fur: Rabbits have a dense, soft coat. They undergo seasonal molting. Fur should be lustrous and free of mats, alopecia, or ectoparasites.
Rabbits lack footpads; the plantar surface of the feet is covered with dense fur only.
Rex breeds have thinner foot fur and are predisposed to pododermatitis.


Open inguinal rings: The inguinal canals remain open throughout life in both sexes. In males, the testicles can be retracted into the abdomen. This has implications for castration technique (the inguinal rings should be closed during neutering to prevent herniation).
Syringe-like (needle-like) claws: Sharp claws that can cause significant scratches to handlers. Regular nail trimming is recommended.


Special Senses
Eyes

Rabbits have laterally placed eyes providing a nearly 360-degree field of vision with a small blind spot directly in front of the nose and directly behind the head.
Large, prominent globes with a large corneal surface.
Retrobulbar venous plexus: A large venous sinus behind the globe. This is important clinically because retrobulbar abscesses (commonly from molar tooth root elongation) and retrobulbar fat deposits can cause exophthalmos.
Third eyelid (nictitating membrane): Present and well-developed. Contains the Harderian gland.
Meibomian glands: Present in the eyelids. The secretion of the Harderian gland contains porphyrins, which may cause a reddish-brown discoloration around the eyes (can be mistaken for blood).
Pupillary light reflex (PLR): Relatively slow and incomplete compared to dogs and cats. Both consensual and direct PLR are present but may be subtle.
Nasolacrimal duct: Single punctum on the lower eyelid. The duct follows a tortuous course through the maxilla near the tooth roots, opening at the nasal punctum. Susceptible to obstruction from dental disease.

Ears

Large pinnae with extensive vascularization, serving as the primary organ for thermoregulation. Rabbits dissipate heat through vasodilation of the ear vasculature.
Central ear artery: Runs along the dorsal midline of the pinna. Used for arterial blood gas sampling.
Marginal ear vein (lateral ear vein): Located on the lateral edge of the pinna. Used for venipuncture and IV catheter placement.
Caudal ear vein: Located on the caudal/medial aspect of the pinna.
Lop-eared breeds are predisposed to otitis externa and otitis media due to the folded, pendulous ear conformation that impairs ventilation and drainage of the ear canal.

Smell

Rabbits have an excellent sense of smell with a large olfactory epithelium.
The vomeronasal organ (Jacobson's organ) is present and used for pheromone detection.
Nose twitching ("wiggling") is a normal behavior that enhances olfaction.


Respiratory System

Obligate nasal breathers: Rabbits breathe exclusively through their nose under normal circumstances. The elongated soft palate rests on the base of the epiglottis. Open-mouth breathing is a sign of severe respiratory distress and is an emergency.
Small oral cavity and large tongue: Makes endotracheal intubation challenging. Blind intubation or the use of an endoscope is often necessary.
Relatively small thoracic cavity compared to the abdomen. The lungs have relatively small tidal volume. The large abdominal viscera can further compromise respiratory capacity, especially in obese rabbits or those with GI distension.
Thymus: The thymus persists into adulthood in rabbits (does not involute as in other species). It is located in the cranial mediastinum and can be visible on thoracic radiographs as a soft tissue opacity in the cranioventral thorax. It should not be mistaken for a mass.


Body Fat Composition

Subcutaneous fat: Can be extensive, especially in obese rabbits. Contributes to the dewlap in females.
Intra-abdominal fat (falciform fat and mesenteric fat): Can be abundant. In obese rabbits, large fat deposits can impair abdominal palpation and contribute to hepatic lipidosis if the rabbit becomes anorexic.
Retroperitoneal fat: Fat deposits around the kidneys and in the retroperitoneal space.
Retrobulbar fat: Fat deposits behind the eyes. Can contribute to mild exophthalmos in obese rabbits.


Gastrointestinal System

Dental formula: I2/1, C0/0, P3/2, M3/3 = 28 teeth.

All teeth are elodont (open-rooted, continuously growing), including incisors, premolars, and molars.
Growth rate of incisors is approximately 2 mm per week (10-12 cm/year).
The upper incisors have a pair of small peg teeth (second incisors) located directly behind the primary incisors.
There is a wide diastema (gap) between the incisors and premolars due to the absence of canine teeth.
Malocclusion and dental disease are extremely common clinical problems.


Stomach:

The stomach is relatively large, comprising about 15% of GI tract volume.
It has a thin muscular wall and rabbits are unable to vomit due to a well-developed cardiac sphincter.
The stomach is divided into regions: cardia, fundus, body, and pylorus.
The stomach should always contain some ingesta. An empty stomach is abnormal.
The stomach pH is very acidic (pH 1-2), which helps kill ingested bacteria and protease activation.


Small intestine:

Comprised of the duodenum, jejunum, and ileum.
Relatively short compared to the large intestine.
The bile duct and pancreatic duct open into the duodenum.
The sacculus rotundus is a round, lymphoid-rich structure at the ileocecal junction (ileal-cecal-colic junction). It functions as a lymphoid organ (similar to a tonsil for the GI tract).


Large intestine (cecum, colon, and rectum):
Cecum:

The cecum is the largest organ in the rabbit's abdomen, comprising approximately 40% of the total GI tract volume.
It is a thin-walled, coiled, sacculated structure located in the ventral and right abdomen.
The appendix (vermiform appendix) is located at the tip of the cecum. It is rich in lymphoid tissue (gut-associated lymphoid tissue, GALT) and functions as an immune organ.
The cecum is the primary site of microbial fermentation (hindgut fermenter). The resident microbiota (primarily anaerobic bacteria) ferment fiber to produce volatile fatty acids (VFAs), which are an important energy source.
Normal cecal content is a homogeneous, olive-green, pasty material with a characteristic odor.

Colon:

The colon is divided into the proximal colon and the distal colon, separated by the fusus coli.
Proximal colon: Contains haustrations (sacculations) and is the site where separation of digestible and indigestible fiber occurs. This is critical for the formation of cecotrophs versus hard fecal pellets.
Fusus coli: A unique structure (pacemaker) that acts as a physiological sphincter between the proximal and distal colon. It controls the separation mechanism and determines whether cecotrophs or hard fecal pellets are produced. It functions as a colonic pacemaker, controlling motility patterns.
Distal colon: Produces the final hard fecal pellets through water reabsorption and mucus coating.


Cecotrophy (coprophagy):

Rabbits produce two types of fecal material:
Hard fecal pellets: Round, dry, fibrous pellets produced during the day. These represent the indigestible fiber portion.
Cecotrophs (soft feces, "night feces"): Soft, mucus-coated clusters of dark, grape-like pellets typically produced in the early morning or at night. These are rich in B vitamins, volatile fatty acids, microbial proteins, and other nutrients.


Rabbits ingest cecotrophs directly from the anus as part of normal digestive physiology. This is essential for adequate nutrition.
Cecotrophs should not be confused with diarrhea. True diarrhea in rabbits is an emergency.


GI transit time: Approximately 4-5 hours for the entire GI tract. Fiber is essential to maintain normal GI motility. A high-fiber diet (primarily grass hay) is critical for dental health and GI function.

GI stasis (ileus): The most common GI disorder in rabbits. Caused by decreased motility of the GI tract, leading to dehydration and impaction of stomach and cecal contents. Predisposing factors include low-fiber diet, dehydration, stress, pain, dental disease, and obesity. This is a medical emergency.



Liver

The liver is composed of four main lobes: right, left (divided into medial and lateral), caudate, and quadrate.
Rabbits have a gallbladder.
The primary bile pigment is biliverdin (not bilirubin as in dogs and cats), giving the bile a green color.
Rabbits are susceptible to hepatic lipidosis (fatty liver disease), particularly obese rabbits that become anorexic. Rapid fat mobilization leads to hepatic fat accumulation and liver failure.
Hepatic coccidiosis (Eimeria stiedae) is a parasitic disease that affects the bile ducts and liver, causing white nodular lesions.


Musculoskeletal System

Lightweight skeleton: The skeleton comprises only about 7-8% of total body weight (compared to ~13% in cats). This makes rabbit bones relatively fragile and susceptible to fractures.
Powerful hind limbs: The hind legs are very muscular and powerful, adapted for jumping and running. If a rabbit kicks out forcefully while unsupported (e.g., during improper handling), it can fracture its own lumbar spine, leading to spinal cord injury and hind limb paralysis.
Seven lumbar vertebrae: The lumbar spine is long and vulnerable to fracture, particularly at the L7-S1 junction.
Flexion of the spine: Rabbits naturally adopt a hunched posture. Forced extension of the spine should be avoided.
Dewclaws: Rabbits have 5 digits on the forelimbs (including a dewclaw) and 4 digits on the hind limbs.


Urinary System
Kidneys

Rabbits have two kidneys. The right kidney is more cranial and the left kidney is more caudal and mobile.
Kidneys are unipapillate (single renal papilla).
Rabbits excrete excess calcium through the kidneys (rather than through the bile as in most other mammals). This results in characteristically thick, creamy, white-to-orange urine with high calcium carbonate content.
Normal urine pH is alkaline (pH 8-9).

Urine Characteristics

Normal rabbit urine can range in color from yellow to orange to red-brown due to porphyrin and other plant pigment excretion. This is normal and should not be confused with hematuria.
Urine is normally turbid and thick due to calcium carbonate crystals.
True hematuria can be differentiated from pigmenturia by urinalysis and urine dipstick testing.
Excessive calcium in the diet can lead to urinary sludge (hypercalciuria) and urolithiasis (calcium carbonate stones).


Reproductive System
Female

Rabbits have a duplex uterus (two separate uterine horns, each with its own cervix). There is no uterine body.
Rabbits are induced ovulators: ovulation occurs in response to mating (coitus), not on a regular cycle. Therefore, they do not have a true estrous cycle but are in an almost continuous state of receptivity.
Gestation period: 29-35 days (average 31 days).
Litter size: 4-10 kits (variable by breed).
Kits are born altricial (blind, deaf, and hairless).
Does nurse their kits only once or twice daily (typically at dawn and dusk), for only a few minutes each time. This is normal and should not be interpreted as maternal neglect.
Uterine adenocarcinoma is the most common neoplasm in intact female rabbits. The incidence increases dramatically with age:
Up to 50-80% of intact does over 5-6 years of age may develop uterine adenocarcinoma.
It can metastasize to the lungs, liver, and other organs.
Ovariohysterectomy (spaying) is strongly recommended for all non-breeding female rabbits, ideally by 6 months to 1 year of age.


Other reproductive disorders include pyometra, endometrial hyperplasia, and endometrial aneurysms.

Male

Testicles: Large, elongated, and positioned in the inguinal region cranial to the penis. Males have open inguinal rings, allowing the testicles to be retracted into the abdomen.
Castration: Recommended for behavioral management and to prevent breeding. The inguinal rings should be closed during the castration procedure to prevent intestinal herniation.
The penis is directed caudally (posteriorly) in the resting position. The penis can be extruded from the prepuce for examination.
Sexual maturity: 6-10 months of age (varies by breed; smaller breeds mature earlier).
Male rabbits can remain fertile for 4-6 weeks after castration due to residual sperm in the reproductive tract.
Breeding onset (buck): 6-10 months of age.

lab3/oral-exam.html.body:
Clinical Anatomy and Oral Examination
Extraoral Examination
Perform a systematic extraoral examination of the head in the rabbit and guinea pig. Identify the following structures by palpation and visual inspection:
Maxillofacial Palpation

Mandibular glands (paired) — palpate ventral to the mandible.
Sublingual glands — located rostral to the mandibular glands.
Mandibular lymph node — located caudoventral to the mandibular gland.
Zygomatic arch — palpate the lateral aspect of the skull.
Maxilla — palpate the lateral and ventral aspects.
Facies cribrosa (rabbit) — the perforated surface of the maxilla, lateral to the nasal bone; unique to rabbits.
Infraorbital foramen (rabbit) — located rostral to the orbit on the maxilla.
Hiatus infraorbitalis (guinea pig) — equivalent region in guinea pigs; corresponds to an open infraorbital canal.
Orbit — palpate the bony rim.
Mandible — palpate the ventral border and lateral body.
Incisure for facial vessels (rabbit) — a palpable notch on the ventral border of the mandible.
Angular process — the caudoventral projection of the mandible.

Temporomandibular Joint
Palpate the temporomandibular joint (TMJ) while opening and closing the mouth. Evaluate range of motion and symmetry.
Occlusion
Evaluate the following:

Incisor occlusion — assess alignment, length, and chisel shape of the incisors.
Premolar/molar occlusion — assess the occlusal plane of the cheek teeth.
Masticatory movement — observe the rostrocaudal (rabbit) or laterolateral (guinea pig) jaw excursion.

Lips and Cheeks
Identify the following:

Mucocutaneous junction — the border between haired skin and oral mucosa.
Vestibule — the space between the lips/cheeks and the dental arcade.
Philtrum — the median cleft of the upper lip.


Oral Examination
Instruments
Familiarize yourself with the instruments used for the oral examination:

Cheek dilator (pouch dilator/tabletop retractor)
Dental table (tabletop oral speculum)
Small rigid endoscope (2.7 mm, 30 degree)



Dental instruments: cheek dilator, dental table, and endoscope used for oral examination of rabbits and rodents.


Positioning the Animal
Place the animal in sternal recumbency. Position the head with the dental table to open the mouth and retract the cheeks with the pouch dilator. Insert the endoscope to visualize the oral cavity.


Close-up view of the dental table setup for oral examination.




Dental table and endoscope positioned for intraoral examination.


Structures to Identify in the Oral Cavity
Oral Mucous Membrane

Oral mucous membrane — the lining of the oral cavity.
Alveolar mucosa — the loosely attached mucosa covering the alveolar bone.
Mucogingival junction — the boundary between alveolar mucosa and attached gingiva.
Attached gingiva — the keratinized tissue firmly bound to the underlying periosteum.

Floor of the Mouth and Tongue

Lingual frenulum — the mucosal fold connecting the tongue to the floor of the mouth.
Torus of the tongue — the prominent dorsal elevation of the caudal tongue.
Intraoral panniculus of the lower lip (guinea pig) — a mucosal fold on the inner surface of the lower lip unique to guinea pigs.

Hard Palate

Incisive papilla — the small elevation on the midline of the hard palate, just caudal to the incisors.
Palatine raphe — the midline ridge of the hard palate.
Palatine rugae — the transverse ridges of the hard palate.
Oropharynx — the caudal portion of the oral cavity leading to the pharynx.
Soft palate — the caudal continuation of the hard palate; note it extends ventral to the tongue in rabbits creating a narrow oropharyngeal isthmus.
Palatine sulcus — the groove along the lateral margin of the hard palate adjacent to the cheek teeth.
Palatine tonsils — lymphoid tissue located in the tonsillary sinus.

Identify the Teeth
Identify all teeth present and note the dental formula for each species:

Endoscopic view of the rabbit oral cavity showing the cheek teeth.




Diagram of the rabbit skull showing tooth positions and dental nomenclature.


Structure and Occlusion
Incisor teeth:
All teeth in rabbits and rodents are aradicular hypsodont (elodont) — they are continuously growing (open-rooted) with no true anatomical root. The incisors have enamel only on the labial (outer) surface. The softer dentin on the lingual (inner) surface wears faster, creating the characteristic chisel shape. In rabbits, the maxillary incisors (I1) have a longitudinal groove on the labial surface. The small peg teeth (I3) sit directly palatal to the main upper incisors. The mandibular incisors are longer than the maxillary incisors and occlude between the peg teeth and the main upper incisors.
Premolar and molar teeth (cheek teeth):
The cheek teeth are also aradicular hypsodont. They have a lophodont occlusal surface pattern with transverse enamel ridges. In rabbits, the maxillary cheek teeth have a slight buccal curvature, and the mandibular cheek teeth have a slight lingual curvature. The normal occlusal plane is flat, with mandibular cheek teeth slightly narrower than the maxillary arcade. Enamel folds create cutting ridges on the occlusal surface for efficient grinding of fibrous plant material.
Chart One Quadrant
Using the dental chart provided in Appendix B, chart one quadrant of the oral cavity for your specimen. Record the crown length, presence of spurs, mobility, and any abnormalities noted.
Comparative Odontology
Compare the dental anatomy of the rabbit with that of the guinea pig. Note the differences in dental formula, skull shape, and dental structure.

lab3/occlusal-adjustments.html.title: Occlusal Adjustments
lab3/occlusal-adjustments.html.body:
Occlusal Adjustments of Incisors, Premolars and Molars
Premolars and Molars
Instruments

Straight handpiece (low-speed)
Medium round diamond bur
Cement spatula
Tongue spatula
Q-tips

Procedure
Using the endoscope for visualization, perform occlusal adjustment of the premolars and molars (cheek teeth):

Place the round diamond bur on the straight handpiece (low-speed).
Under endoscopic guidance, identify the cheek teeth that require adjustment (e.g., spurs, uneven occlusal plane, elongated crowns).
Use a cement spatula to protect the soft tissues (buccal mucosa and tongue) from the rotating bur.
Apply the rotating diamond bur to the occlusal surface of the cheek teeth with a light touch. The goal is to restore a normal, flat occlusal plane.
Work progressively, removing small amounts of tooth at a time. Frequently reassess the occlusal plane with the endoscope.
Avoid thermal damage: use a light, intermittent touch rather than continuous pressure. No cooling fluid is used, so brief contact is essential to prevent overheating the tooth and damaging the pulp.
Use Q-tips to remove debris from the oral cavity during the procedure.

Perform the Adjustment
Perform occlusal adjustment of the cheek teeth on your specimen. Restore a normal occlusal plane.


Occlusal adjustment procedure on a rabbit.



Incisors
Instruments

High-speed angled handpiece
Cylindrical diamond bur
Tongue depressor

Procedure
Perform crown reduction of the incisors:

Remove the pouch dilator to access the incisors.
Place a tongue depressor between the upper and lower incisors to protect the opposing teeth and soft tissues during the procedure.
Attach the cylindrical diamond bur to the high-speed angled handpiece.
Reduce the crown height of the incisor to restore the normal chisel-shaped occlusal plane.
Avoid exposing the pulp cavity — leave at least 0.5 mm coronal to the gingival papilla to maintain an adequate safety margin.
Shape the incisor to restore the proper chisel shape and angle of the occlusal surface.

Perform the Adjustment
Perform incisor crown reduction on your specimen. After the adjustment, clean the oral cavity with Q-tips and remove any debris.
Check Occlusion
After completing all adjustments, check both premolar-molar occlusion and incisor occlusion:

The cheek teeth occlusal plane should be flat and even.
The mandibular incisors should rest between the maxillary peg teeth (I3) and the main upper incisors (I1).
The chisel edge of the mandibular incisor should contact the palatal surface of the maxillary I1.



Checking incisor occlusion after crown reduction. The mandibular incisors should occlude properly between the peg teeth and the maxillary incisors.

lab3/extraction.html.title: Extraction of Incisors
lab3/extraction.html.body:
Extraction of Incisors
Instruments

Swann-Morton scalpel handle with straight surgical blade
Crossley rabbit incisor luxator
Cryer extraction forceps

Procedure: Mandibular Incisor Extraction

Using the scalpel blade, incise the gingival attachment around the incisor to be extracted. Sever the periodontal ligament circumferentially.
Insert the Crossley rabbit incisor luxator into the periodontal ligament space along the mesial surface of the tooth.
Advance the luxator in the apical direction, following the curvature of the tooth.
Work the luxator in an alternating mesial and distal fashion, progressively loosening the tooth in its alveolus.
Be cautious not to apply excessive lateral force that could cause bone expansion or fracture of the alveolar bone.
Do not use the luxator as a lever — the instrument should be used to sever the periodontal ligament, not to pry the tooth from the alveolus.

Use of Extraction Forceps
Once the tooth is sufficiently mobile:

Grasp the tooth gently with the Cryer extraction forceps.
Intrude gently — apply slight inward (apical) pressure to further break down remaining periodontal ligament fibers.
Slide the tooth out of the curved alveolus, following the natural curvature of the tooth. Apply slight longitudinal traction along the axis of the tooth.
Avoid leverage, torque, or premature traction — the tooth is long and curved, and premature or forceful extraction can fracture the tooth, leaving the apex behind.

Check for Germinal Tissue
After extraction, inspect the apex of the tooth for the presence of germinal tissue (the soft tissue cap at the apex). If present, this confirms complete extraction and ensures the tooth will not regrow.
Repeat for Maxillary Incisor
Repeat the extraction procedure for the maxillary incisor (I1). Note that the maxillary incisors have a different curvature than the mandibular incisors — the maxillary incisors curve in approximately 180 degrees, whereas the mandibular incisors have a more gentle curve.


Steps of the incisor extraction procedure showing luxator insertion and tooth mobilization.




Extraction instruments and extracted incisors. Note the germinal tissue at the apex of the extracted teeth.




Cryer extraction forceps used for incisor extraction in rabbits.
